00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:09.390
So photons-- also
called light, also

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.270
called electric
magnetic radiation--

00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:17.070
may be described by their
energy, by their wavelength,

00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:20.430
or by their frequency.

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:23.880
Whereas electrons, which
are sometimes also called

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:28.590
photoelectrons, may be described
by their kinetic energy,

00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:34.150
their velocity, and, as you'll
see later, by their wavelength.

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:36.480
So you'll be given
problems where,

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:38.399
given different
pieces of information,

00:06:38.399 --> 00:06:40.690
you have to think about how
you're going to convert it.

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:42.940
You've got to think about
am I talking about a photon?

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:44.940
Am I talking about an electron?

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:47.800
And you also want to
think about units.

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:51.780
You'll sometimes be
told about energy in eVs

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:54.660
and sometimes be told
about energies in joules.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:56.520
So this is a conversion factor.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:06:59.085
All conversion factors are
given to you on the exam.

00:06:59.085 --> 00:07:03.160
You do not need to memorize
any kind of conversion factor.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.250
But you need to be
aware, when someone

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:09.090
said joules, what's that a unit
for, or eV, what's that a unit

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:10.990
for.

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:11.490
All right.

00:07:11.490 --> 00:07:14.730
So now we're going to do
and in-class demonstration

00:07:14.730 --> 00:07:16.430
of the photoelectric effect.

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:19.200
But before we actually
do the experiment,

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:23.160
we're going to predict what
